H.B. 541
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Mar 26, 2025
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH30232-LUae-11B
Short Title: Opt. Top-2 Same-Day Primary Runoff/Elections. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Morey.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ALLOW POLITICAL PARTIES THE OPTION OF USING A TOP-TWO,
3 SAME-DAY RUNOFF METHOD IN SELECTED PRIMARIES THAT MAY TRIGGER A
4 RUNOFF.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. Article 10 of Chapter 163 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
7 a new section to read:
8 "§ 163-111.5. Optional top-two, same-day primary runoff method.
9 (a) Purpose. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law to the contrary and except as
10 otherwise required by federal law, the purpose of this section is to establish a method (modeled
11 on the "top-two instant runoff" election to the State Court of Appeals in 2010) for an optional
12 top-two, same-day primary runoff when no candidate receives thirty percent (30%) of the vote
13 in a primary for designated elected offices. Implementing this method will (i) help assure
14 nominees have broader support, (ii) avoid voters returning to the polls in expensive, low-turnout
15 second primaries, and (iii) allow political parties to optionally use this top-two runoff method in
16 selected primaries that may trigger a runoff.
17 (b) Scope. – The method described in this section shall apply to primaries for any federal
18 or State office, including United States Senate, United States House of Representatives, Council
19 of State, member of the State Senate, member of the State House of Representatives, and elected
20 judicial and county offices. It shall not apply to presidential primaries.
21 (c) Party-Optional Use. – As stipulated in G.S. 163-111, when no candidate has received
22 a substantial plurality of total votes cast in a primary, the second highest-polling candidate may
23 request a runoff. Pursuant to this section, a political party shall have the option to use a top-two,
24 same-day runoff method for a primary if the party determines a divided vote may prevent one
25 candidate from attaining thirty percent (30%) of the vote and trigger a runoff.
26 (d) Top-Two Runoff Method. – In a multicandidate primary selected for a top-two,
27 same-day runoff, a voter may rank up to three candidates in order of preference. If after an initial
28 tabulation no candidate attains thirty percent (30%) of the first-preference votes, the two
29 candidates with the most first-preference votes shall advance to a "runoff." All other candidates
30 are eliminated. The ballots from the eliminated candidates shall be tabulated and those marked
31 with either of the runoff candidates as a second preference shall be counted. Then, the remaining
32 ballots from the eliminated candidates shall be tabulated and those marked with the runoff
33 candidates as a third preference shall be counted. The first-, second-, and third-preference votes
34 shall be added together and the runoff candidate with the most votes shall be declared the winner.
35 Should the General Assembly decide to adjust the substantial plurality requirement, provisions
